				As I used to tell my professors that would spout of about the &quot;Real World&quot; scenarios. Working in the real world and academia are two different things. I work for a corporation that is a peer to Sony in size and corporate stupidity.  SOE did not tell people that they were removing the numbering system due to marketing concerns until people starting voicing their disatisfaction and they had no choice but to acknowledge the true reason becasue too many people had called them for what they are.<BR>
<BR>
This is the way of big business. Don't ask for permission, beg for forgiveness. Whether it be the gov't catching them violating some Federal Trade Act, ot god forbid screwing over their own client base.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Bottom line is there will always some upper middle management that comes up with a &quot;Brilliant Scheme&quot; to make the company more money at the expense of the real contibutors to the  company. The Customers! And then when it back fires the upper manqgement just fires the originator or the idea and disavows any knowledge of it. <BR>
<BR>
 And while it doesn't always work correctly or may be the best system it is obvious that SOE does read these boards or they would not have sent out the disclaimer.<BR>
<BR>
So to the &quot;Teacher&quot; that came out with the wonderful words of wisdom please let me know what state, county you are from so I can pull my kids out of that school if you happen to be their teacher.<BR>
<BR>
Academia and the &quot;Real World&quot; are two different things, and if you think that telling people to pull their money (unless you plan to organize a controlling interest) is a bright idea then you know nothing of the real world and might want to try it before you teach another semester.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
